<Author>neyu
<Content>This hotel spoiled our holiday We booked three nights at the ITC Hotel online after checking their website (nice photos) and the location. Mistake number one was not checking TripAdvisor.On arrival, the side-street location overlooking the canal seemed great. But after checking in we were then led round the corner to a grotty ex-hotel on the main road, up some narrow, steep stairs and ushered into what can best be described as a space vaguely resembling a hotel room. Welcome to room no.23. Everything was there - walls, ceiling, bed, window, shower, toilet, sink, etc, but it looked like it had been put together by the local homeless people after a long night on the booze and weed.Our first night (Saturday night) was the noisiest night we have ever experienced in a hotel, and we hardly slept, if at all. Not a good sign.The following morning we went straight round to reception to ask to be moved to a quieter room, only to be told the hotel was fully booked (its the weekend ya'see - we're busy). We were offered a quieter room at the back of the main hotel building for the third night, at which we, relunctantly, agreed. During these high-level negotiations they constantly warned us that this new room was smaller than the one we were currently in. And we stupidly thought that was simply not possible! Oh, how wrong we were....The second night initially proved quieter (fewer drunks outside at 1 in the morning), although still in the room overlooking the main road, so we got to enjoy trams trundling past every 15 minutes until some time after midnight. That is, until about half past two when the fire alarm went off. Or rather, stayed on for about 5 minutes, which is a long time when a loud sounder is blasting you from deep slumber, scaring my wife half to death (not a good thing for a pregnant woman).Day three and we packed our bag, said goodbye to number 23, and looked forward to breakfast and a new room. We headed off into Amsterdam filled with a sense of hope. Oh, how innocent and naive.On return to the hotel we eventually found room number 19. There are photos and a description of this room already on this site in the review by Braxn. Suffice it say this room suffers from Inverse Tardis Syndrome - its smaller on the inside! Yes, this room _was_ smaller than the one we had come from. And the lack of any visible view from any kind of window was very depressing. Indeed, the view from the shower cubicle window is of a ventilation/light shaft.Overall, this hotel is the worst hotel we have ever stayed in. Don't be put off by the gayest hotel in Amsterdam line - its a cheap shot just to get web hits. The only recommendation we can offer is to stay AWAY from this hotel. 
